A '''chronosequence''' (in [[forest sciences]]) is a set of forested sites that share similar attributes but are of different ages.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Edward Arnold |last=Johnson |page=5 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=GfyIjLypngIC&pg=PA5&dq=%22chronosequence%22#v=onepage&q=%22chronosequence%22&f=false |title=Plant disturbance ecology: the process and the response |isbn=978-0-12-088778-1 |publisher=Academic Press |year=2007}}</ref> Since many processes in [[forest ecology]] take a long time (decades or centuries) to develop, chronosequence methods are used to represent and study the time-dependent development of a forest. [[Fieldata|Field data]] from a chronosequence can be collected in a short period of several months. For example, chronosequences are often used to study the changes in plant communities during [[Ecological succession|succession]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Knops |first1=Johannes M.H. |author1-link= Johannes M.H. Knops |last2=Tilman |first2=David |author2-link=David Tilman |title=Dynamics of soil nitrogen and carbon accumulation for 61 years after agricultural abandonment |journal=Ecology |volume=81 |issue=1 |pages=88–98 |year=2000 |doi=10.2307/177136|jstor=177136 }}</ref> A classic example of using '''chronosequences''' to study [[ecological succession]] is in the study of plant and microbial succession in recently deglactiated zones. For example, a study from 2005 used the distance from the nose of a glacier as a proxy for site age.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tscherko|first1=Dagmar|last2=Hammesfahr|first2=Ute|last3=Zeltner|first3=Georg|last4=Kandeler|first4=Ellen|last5=Böcker|first5=Reinhard|title=Plant succession and rhizosphere microbial communities in a recently deglaciated alpine terrain|journal=Basic and Applied Ecology|date=5 August 2005|volume=6|issue=4|pages=367–383|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1439179105000356|doi=10.1016/j.baae.2005.02.004}}</ref>
A common assumption in establishing '''chronosequences''' is that no other variable besides age (such as various [[abiotic|abiotic components]] and [[biotic components]]) has changed between sites of interest. Because this assumption cannot always be tested for environmental study sites, the use of chronosequences in field successional studies has recently been debated.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Johnson|first1=Edward|last2=Miyanishi|first2=Kiyoko|title=Testing the assumptions of chronosequences in succession|journal=Ecology Letters|date=13 March 2008|volume=11|issue=5|pages=419–431|doi=10.1111/j.1461-0248.2008.01173.x|pmid=18341585}}</ref>
